'''[[Scientific misconduct]]''' is the violation of the standard codes of [[scholarly method|scholarly conduct]] and [[ethics|ethical behavior]] in the publication of professional [[science|scientific research]]. A ''[[The Lancet|Lancet]]'' review on ''Handling of Scientific Misconduct in Scandinavian countries'' gave examples of policy definitions. In Denmark, scientific misconduct is defined as "intention[al] or gross negligence leading to fabrication of the scientific message or a false credit or emphasis given to a scientist", and in Sweden as "intention[al] distortion of the research process by fabrication of data, text, hypothesis, or methods from another researcher's manuscript form or publication; or distortion of the research process in other ways."<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Nylenna M, Andersen D, Dahlquist G, Sarvas M, Aakvaag A | title = Handling of scientific dishonesty in the Nordic countries. National Committees on Scientific Dishonesty in the Nordic Countries | journal = Lancet | volume = 354 | issue = 9172 | pages = 57–61 | date = July 1999 | pmid = 10406378 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(98)07133-5 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Coping with fraud |work=The COPE Report 1999 |pages=11–18 |url=http://www.publicationethics.org.uk/reports/1999/1999pdf3.pdf |format=PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928151119/http://www.publicationethics.org.uk/reports/1999/1999pdf3.pdf |quote=It is 10 years, to the month, since Stephen Lock ... |archive-date=2007-09-28 |access-date=2006-09-02|ref=COPE1999PDF}}</ref>
A 2009 [[systematic review]] and [[meta-analysis]] of survey data found that about 2% of scientists admitted to falsifying, fabricating, or modifying data at least once.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fanelli D | title = How many scientists fabricate and falsify research? A systematic review and meta-analysis of survey data | journal = PLOS One | volume = 4 | issue = 5 | page = e5738 | date = May 2009 | pmid = 19478950 | pmc = 2685008 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0005738 }}</ref> {{dynamic list}}
== Biomedical sciences == * Anna Ahimastos-Lamberti (Australia), a former medical researcher, admitted to fabricating scientific results published in numerous major international medical journals.<ref>{{cite web |title=High-profile researcher made up scientific results |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-09-17/high-profile-researcher-admits-to-fabricating-scientific-results/6781958 |website=ABC News |accessdate=27 September 2018 |language=en-AU |date=17 September 2015}}</ref> As a result, two journal articles about a three-year clinical trial involving a medication used to treat hypertension were retracted.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Nicky |title=Blood pressure research by scientist Anna Ahimastos retracted over faked data |url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/blood-pressure-research-by-scientist-anna-ahimastos-retracted-over-faked-data-20150917-gjoqh0.html |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=27 September 2018 |language=en |date=17 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Australian scientist fabricated data |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-34275648 |website=BBC News |accessdate=27 September 2018 |date=17 September 2015}}</ref> * [[Bharat Aggarwal]] (US), a former Ransom Horne, Jr. Distinguished Professor of Cancer Research at the [[University of Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center]],<ref>{{cite web | title = MD Anderson’s Bharat Aggarwal threatens to sue Retraction Watch |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2013/04/10/md-andersons-bharat-aggarwal-threatens-to-sue-retraction-watch/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2013-04-10|access-date=2018-04-12}}</ref> resigned his position after fraud was discovered in 65 papers published by him in the area of [[curcumin]] as a treatment for cancer.<ref>{{cite web | title = M.D. Anderson professor under fraud probe | url = http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/M-D-Anderson-professor-under-fraud-probe-3360037.phpV | work = Chiron }}</ref> Aggarwal has had 28 of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Cancer journals retract 10 papers, flag 8 more, and apologize for the delay |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/09/04/cancer-journals-retract-10-papers-flag-8-more-and-apologize-for-the-delay/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-09-04|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref> * [[Elias Alsabti]] (Iraq, US), was a medical practitioner who posed as a biomedical researcher. He plagiarized as many as 60 papers in the field of cancer research, many with non-existent co-authors.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Broad WJ | title = Would-be academician pirates papers | journal = Science | volume = 208 | issue = 4451 | pages = 1438–40 | date = June 1980 | pmid = 17796686 | doi = 10.1126/science.208.4451.1438 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Woolf P | title = Fraud in science: how much, how serious? | journal = The Hastings Center Report | volume = 11 | issue = 5 | pages = 9–14 | date = October 1981 | pmid = 7309502 | doi = 10.2307/3561291 | jstor = 3561291 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Miller|first=David | name-list-format = vanc |title=Research Fraud in the Behavioral and Biomedical Sciences|date=1992|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=Hoboken, NJ|isbn=978-0471520689|page=80|chapter=Plagiarism: The Case of Elias A.K. Alsbati}}</ref> * Piero Anversa (US, Italy) and [[Annarosa Leri]] (US, Italy), collaborators and former researchers at Harvard University, were found in a 2014 investigation to have "manipulated and falsified" data in their research on [[Endogenous cardiac stem cell|endogenous cardiac stem cells]], and to have included "false scientific information" in grant applications.<ref>{{cite web | title = Partners Healthcare and Brigham and Women’s Hospital Agree to Pay $10 Million to Resolve Research Fraud Allegations |url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-ma/pr/partners-healthcare-and-brigham-and-women-s-hospital-agree-pay-10-million-resolve|publisher=United States department of Justice|date=2017-04-27|access-date=2018-03-19}}</ref> Anversa and Leri lost a lawsuit they brought against Harvard that claimed the investigation had damaged their reputations.<ref>{{cite web | title = Judge dismisses cardiac stem cell researchers’ lawsuit against Harvard |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2015/07/29/judge-dismisses-cardiac-stem-cell-researchers-lawsuit-against-harvard/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-07-29|access-date=2018-03-19}}</ref> Anversa and Leri have one retracted and eight corrected publications.<ref>{{cite web | title = Stem cell researchers investigated for misconduct recommended for roles at Italy’s NIH |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/03/14/stem-cell-researchers-investigated-for-misconduct-recommended-for-roles-at-italys-nih/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-03-14|access-date=2018-03-19}}</ref> In October 2018, Harvard University and Brigham and Women's Hospital called for an additional 31 paper retractions after many failed replications of their work.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/15/health/piero-anversa-fraud-retractions.html|title=Harvard Calls for Retraction of Dozens of Studies by Noted Cardiologist|access-date=2018-10-16|language=en}}</ref> * Edward Awh and graduate student David Anderson (US), formerly of the [[University of Oregon]], retracted nine of their publications due to data fabrication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/education/index.ssf/2015/07/uo_grad_student_falsified_rese.html |title=Feds find UO grad student falsified research data, voiding results of four studies; The Oregonian |publisher=oreganlive.com |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://retractionwatch.com/2016/04/19/two-more-retractions-bring-total-to-9-for-neuroscience-duo/ |title=Two more retractions bring total to 9 for neuroscience duo; Retraction Watch |publisher=retractionwatch.com |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref> This included an action identified by [[The Scientist (magazine)]] as a Top 10 Retraction of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/44895/title/The-Top-10-Retractions-of-2015/ |title=The Top 10 Retractions of 2015; The Scientist |publisher=the-scientist.com |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref> * Werner Bezwoda (South Africa), formerly of the [[University of Witwatersrand]], admitted to scientific misconduct in trials on [[HDC/BMT|high-dose chemotherapy on breast cancer]], stating that he had "committed a serious breach of scientific honesty and integrity."<ref name=pmid10768448>{{cite journal | vauthors = Weiss RB, Rifkin RM, Stewart FM, Theriault RL, Williams LA, Herman AA, Beveridge RA | title = High-dose chemotherapy for high-risk primary breast cancer: an on-site review of the Bezwoda study | journal = Lancet | volume = 355 | issue = 9208 | pages = 999–1003 | date = March 2000 | pmid = 10768448 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(00)90024-2 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Breast Cancer Researcher Admits Falsifying Data |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/02/05/us/breast-cancer-researcher-admits-falsifying-data.html|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=2000-02-05|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Key Breast Cancer Study Was a Fraud |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/apr/27/news/mn-56336|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=2001-04-27|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> * Philippe Bois (US), a former postdoctoral fellow in biochemistry at [[St. Jude Children’s Research Hospital]] was found by the [[United States Office of Research Integrity|Office of Research Integrity]] to have used misleading data for one image in a 2005 ''[[Journal of Cell Biology]]'' paper and completely faked another image in a ''[[Molecular and Cellular Biology]]'' article published the same year. The JCB paper was retracted later in May 2007 and the MCB paper was corrected.<ref>{{cite web | title = St. Jude postdoc faked images: A former postdoctoral researcher at St. Jude Children’s Research Hospital fudged images published in two papers, one of which has since been retracted.|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/news-opinion/st-jude-postdoc-faked-images-42317/|publisher=The Scientist|date=2011-06-22|access-date=2018-07-10}}</ref> * [[Joachim Boldt]] (Germany), an anesthesiologist formerly based at the [[Justus Liebig University Giessen]], was stripped of his professorship and criminally investigated for forgery in his research studies.<ref>Heidi Blake, Holly Watt and Robert Winnett. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/8360667/Millions-of-surgery-patients-at-risk-in-drug-research-fraud-scandal.html "Millions of surgery patients at risk in drug research fraud scandal"]. ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', 03 Mar 2011 (retrieved 2011-03-03)</ref> Boldt has had 96 of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = When you have 94 retractions, what’s two more? |url=https://retractionwatch.com/category/joachim-boldt-retractions/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2017-03-01|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> * C. David Bridges (US), a researcher at [[Purdue University]] and formerly at [[Baylor College of Medicine]], was found by a [[NIH]] investigation panel to have stolen ideas from a rival's manuscript that Bridges had been asked to review, and used that information to produce and publish his own research.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1989/07/13/nih-accuses-biologist-of-stealing-ideas-from-rival-researcher/fd8a3122-c461-49d8-bd05-c8b99e930f2d/|title=NIH Accuses Biologist of Stealing Ideas From Rival Researcher|publisher=The Washington Post|date=1989-07-13|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-07-17/local/me-2884_1_scientific-fraud|title=Journal Admits Fraud Fears|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=1989-07-17|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> The investigating panel described Bridges' conduct as "an egregious misconduct of science that undermines the entire concept and practice of scientific experimentation and ethical responsibility,"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/07/12/us/question-of-scientific-fakery-is-raised-in-inquiry.html|title=Question of scientific fakery is raised in inquiry|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1989-07-12|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> with NIH later stripping Bridges' of his funding.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/pdf/10.1021/cen-v067n032.p024|title=NIH panel strips researcher of funding after plagiarism review|journal=Chemical & Engineering News|volume=67|issue=32|page=24|publisher=American Chemical Society|date=1989-08-07|access-date=2018-04-18|doi=10.1021/cen-v067n032.p024|last1=Zurer|first1=Pamela S}}</ref> * [[Silvia Bulfone-Paus]] (Germany, UK), an immunologist at the [[Research Center Borstel]] and the [[University of Manchester]], has had 13 of her publications retracted following investigations of alleged scientific misconduct involving image manipulation.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/news.2010.671 |title=German research centre widens misconduct probe |journal=Nature |year=2010 |last1=Schiermeier |first1=Quirin | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Marcus|first=Adam | name-list-format = vanc |title=Bulfone-Paus retraction count grows to 13 with one in Transplantation|url=http://retractionwatch.wordpress.com/2011/12/13/bulfone-paus-retraction-count-grows-to-13-with-one-in-transplantation/|work=Retraction Watch|publisher=Retraction Watch|access-date=17 January 2012}}</ref> * [[Ranjit Chandra]] (Canada), former nutrition researcher at [[Memorial University of Newfoundland]] and self-proclaimed "father of nutritional immunology,"<ref>{{cite web | title = Who is Ranjit Kumar Chandra? A timeline of notoriety | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2016/07/26/who-is-ranjit-kumar-chandra-a-timeline-of-notoriety/|date=2016-07-26|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> was in 2015 stripped of his [[Order of Canada]] membership following accusations of scientific wrongdoing in his research.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disgraced researcher Ranjit Chandra stripped of 1989 Order of Canada|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/disgraced-researcher-ranjit-chandra-stripped-of-1989-order-of-canada/article28084791/|access-date=9 January 2016}}</ref> In 2015 Chandra lost a $132 million case against the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]], which in 2006 presented a documentary in which 10 of Chandra's publications were identified as “fraudulent or highly suspicious;”<ref>{{cite web | title = Nutrition researcher Chandra loses libel case against CBC |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2015/07/31/nutrition-researcher-chandra-loses-libel-case-against-cbc/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2015-07-31|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> Chandra was ordered to pay the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] $1.6 million to cover the defendant's legal fees.<ref>{{cite web | title = Ranjit Chandra ordered to pay $1.6M to cover CBC's legal fees in libel lawsuit |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/chandra-paying-legal-fees-1.3322284|publisher=CBC/Radio Canada|date=2015-11-17|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> At least four of Chandra's publications have been retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Nutrition researcher loses two more papers after misconduct findings come to light | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2016/06/16/nutrition-researcher-loses-two-more-papers-after-misconduct-findings-come-to-light/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2016-06-16|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> * [[Ching-Shih Chen]] (US), the former chair of cancer research at [[The Ohio State University]], was investigated by OSU and the federal Office of Research Integrity after being anonymously reported for falsifying data. The investigation found that he falsified information in at least 11 publications, and that he did not keep any laboratory notebooks on his research, a violation of federal research policies.<ref>{{cite web|title=OSU Professor Falsified Data on Eight Papers, Resigns|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo