anders|url=https://www.pacermonitor.com/public/case/21205255/Croce_v_Sanders|publisher=PacerMonitor LLC|date=2017-04-20|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> and a defamation claim against [[The New York Times]] that in 2018 was largely dismissed,<ref>{{cite web|title=Judge Tosses Researcher’s Libel Claims Against NY Times|url=https://www.courthousenews.com/judge-tosses-researchers-libel-claims-against-ny-times/|publisher=Courthouse News Service|date=2018-11-07|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> has had eight of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Probe into Carlo Croce reached "defensible and reasonable" decisions, says external review|url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/03/05/probe-into-carlo-croce-reached-defensible-and-reasonable-decisions-says-external-review/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-03-05|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> * [[John Darsee]] (US), a cardiologist formerly based at [[Harvard University]], fabricated data in published research articles and more than 100 abstracts and book chapters.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Stewart WW, Feder N | title = The integrity of the scientific literature | journal = Nature | volume = 325 | issue = 6101 | pages = 207–14 | year = 1987 | pmid = 3808019 | doi = 10.1038/325207a0 | bibcode = 1987Natur.325..207S }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Harvard Suspends Doctor For Fraud |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/12/16/us/harvard-suspends-doctor-for-fraud.html |publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1981-12-16|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> In 1983 Darsee was disbarred for ten years by the US [[National Institutes of Health]].<ref>{{cite web | title = U.S. to Penalize Heart Researcher on Fraudulent Project at Harvard |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/02/16/us/us-to-penalize-heart-researcher-on-fraudulent-project-at-harvard.html|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1983-02-16|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> Darsee has had at least 17 of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://retractionwatch.