ses in Deaths of Children |journal=[[Pediatrics (journal)|Pediatrics]] |volume=93 |issue=6 |page=944 |date=June 1994 |pmid= |url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/cgi/content/abstract/93/6/944-b}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = How Two Baby Deaths Led to a Misguided SIDS Theory | url = http://articles.latimes.com/1997/oct/20/health/he-44680|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=1997-10-20|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> In 1997 the editor of [[Pediatrics (journal)]], Jerold Lucey, stated that Steinschneider's original paper on the subject was "seriously flawed" and should not have been published.<ref>{{cite web | title = Setting The Medical Record Straight | url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-09-27/news/9709270164_1_sids-cases-dr-alfred-steinschneider-dr-jerold-lucey|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=1997-09-27|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> * [[Marc Straus]] (US), former Chief of Oncology and Associate Professor of Medicine at [[Boston University Medical Center]], in 1982 admitted to "serious deficiencies," including the use of false data, in research studies he supervised. He also admitted to using ineligible patients in his studies, administering drug dosages different from those in his plan, and not assuring compliance with rules of informed consent.<ref name=UPI>{{cite web |url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1982/05/21/Dr-Marc-J-Straus-a-cancer-researcher-barred-from/1804390801600/ |title=Dr. Marc J. Straus, a cancer researcher barred from... |date=May 21, 1982 |website=[[UPI]] |access-date=August 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = The Commission's Report |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/20/us/doctor-admits-filing-false-data-and-is-barred-from-us-support.html|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=1982-05-20|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/21/us/doctor-denies-role-in-fraud.html |title=Doctor Denies Role in Fraud |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=May 21, 2016 |access-date=August 20, 2016}}</ref> * [[Jon Sudbø]] (Norway), an oncologist and former Associate Professor at the [[University of Oslo]], was found in a 2006 investigation to have manipulated and fabricated data in grant applications and 15 of his research papers.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/02/health/02docs.htm | work=The New York Times | first1=Lawrence K. | last1=Altman | name-list-format = vanc | title=For Science's Gatekeepers, a Credibility Gap | date=2006-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = The Commission's Report | url = http://www.rikshospitalet.no:80/content/res_bibl/6633.pdf | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060920200752/http://www.rikshospitalet.no/content/res_bibl/6633.pdf | archive-date = 2006-09-20 | dead-url = yes | publisher = Rikshospitalet | date = 2006-06-30 | access-date = 2018-03-29 | df = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Case Summary: Sudbo, Jon | url = https://ori.hhs.gov/content/case-summary-sudbo-jon|publisher=US Department of Health and Human Services Office of Research Integrity|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> Sudbø has had 12 of his publications retracted.<ref name="leaderboard"/> * Akio Sugino (Japan), a former molecular biologist and professor at [[Osaka University]], was dismissed from the University following an investigation that revealed he fabricated research data in two of his papers.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Normile D | title = Scientific misconduct. Japan's universities take action | journal = Science | volume = 315 | issue = 5808 | page = 26 | date = January 2007 | pmid = 17204614 | doi = 10.1126/science.315.5808.26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/445240a|title=Misconduct? It's all academic|publisher=Macmillan Publishers Limited|date=2007-01-17|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | first = Sophie L. | last = Rovner | name-list-format = vanc | title = Research Ethics: Experts ponder how best to prevent and respond to scientific misconduct as three Japanese cases conclude |u