A '''violation paradigm''' is a [[scientific method]] where the [[scientist]] perturbs an expected [[Design of experiments|factor]] to look at the subject's following [[reflex|reactions]]. These reactions are believed to be relevant to the [[process]] studied. For example, creating wrong word segmentations in a text will [[Destabilisation|destabilize]] the reader. This warns the [[researcher]] that the respondent's [[brain]] considers the characters are united into words, and not just as a succession of given sets of letters. The process was originally developed by Danks, Bohn & Fear (1983), and proved valid ({{harvnb|Chen|1999|p= }}).

== See also ==
